# Complexity Comparison

| Approach    | Idea                                                               | Time                                                                                                                                                                                       | Space |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ----- |
| Brute Force | Simulate operations until original array returns                   | O(answer × n)                                                                                                                                                                              | O(n)  |
| Better      | Detect cycle lengths and compute LCM incrementally                 | O(n log n)                                                                                                                                                                                 | O(n)  |
| Optimal     | Detect cycles + prime factorization of cycle lengths + modular LCM | O(n√n) in the straightforward factorization shown (acceptable for (n \le 10^4)); with a smallest-prime-factor sieve it becomes (O(n \log \log n)) preprocessing + near (O(n \log n)) total | O(n)  |

### Core takeaway

* A permutation always decomposes into **disjoint cycles**.
* A cycle of length **k** returns to its original state after exactly **k** operations.
* All cycles must return **at the same time**, so the answer is the **Least Common Multiple (LCM)** of all cycle lengths.
* The main challenge is computing that LCM efficiently without overflowing, which is why the prime-factorization approach is often used.
